---

Chris Paik’s essay "The End of Software" is an existential gut punch for anyone whose career is built on writing code. Paik argues that as generative AI drives the marginal cost of creating software down to zero, software itself loses its value as a proprietary asset. It is a brilliant, provocative thesis that shifts the focal point of tech entrepreneurship away from raw engineering and toward data accumulation and distribution. When the code is free, the value accumulates elsewhere.

As an engineer and founder, this forces a radical re-evaluation of our startup strategies. If anyone can prompt a fully functional application into existence, our ability to write neat, performant software ceases to be a competitive advantage. Instead, the focus of product development must pivot to cultivating proprietary data feedback loops and building deeply integrated distribution channels that are incredibly difficult to replicate. The future belongs not to the software creators, but to those who can aggregate trust and own the underlying customer relationship.

### What stuck with me

* **Zero marginal cost**: As the price of writing code approaches zero, software will commoditize completely, stripping away its traditional premium value.
* **Value shift to data**: Defensibility in a post-software era will rely entirely on proprietary data access and deep distribution advantages that cannot be prompted into existence.
* **Developer role transformation**: Engineers must evolve from writing and maintaining lines of code to orchestrating complex systems and managing deep product integration.
